            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the party drink calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed to be more practical than generic
                “cocktail party” guides. Instead of just listing recipes, it
                estimates how many drinks you actually need and converts them
                into bottles, cans and liters.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Estimating total number of drinks</h3>
              <p>We start from a widely used rule of thumb:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Drinks per adult</strong> = 2 drinks for the first
                  hour + 1 drink for each additional hour
                </p>
                <p>For example, for a 4‑hour party:</p>
                <p>Drinks per adult = 2 + (4 − 1) × 1 = 5 drinks</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                We then adjust this baseline with the selected drinking style:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Light</strong>: × 0.7 (business events, brunch, many
                  drivers)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Average</strong>: × 1.0 (typical evening party)</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Heavy</strong>: × 1.3 (cocktail parties, late‑night
                  events)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Alcohol vs non‑alcoholic drinks</h3>
              <p>
                You choose what percentage of total drinks should be alcoholic.
                The rest is allocated to soft drinks, juice and water. This is
                helpful for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Family parties with many kids (low alcohol share)</li>
                <li>After‑work aperitivo (balanced alcohol and soft drinks)</li>
                <li>
                  Cocktail parties (high alcohol share, but still enough water)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Converting drinks into bottles and cans</h3>
              <p>We assume the following standard serving sizes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wine</strong>: 150 ml per glass → ~5 glasses per 750
                  ml bottle
                </li>
                <li><strong>Beer</strong>: 330 ml per bottle/can</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Spirits / cocktails</strong>: 45 ml of spirit per
                  drink
                </li>
                <li><strong>Soft drinks & juice</strong>: 250 ml per glass</li>
                <li><strong>Water</strong>: 250 ml per glass</li>
              </ul>
              <p>From there, we compute:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Bottles of wine</strong> = (wine drinks × 150 ml) ÷
                  750 ml
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Bottles/cans of beer</strong> = (beer drinks × 330 ml)
                  ÷ 330 ml
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Bottles of spirits (0.7 L)</strong> = (spirit drinks ×
                  45 ml) ÷ 700 ml
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Ice estimate</h3>
              <p>
                Ice is essential for cocktails and soft drinks. A safe estimate
                is:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>0.7 kg (≈1.5 lb) of ice per guest</strong> for a 3–4
                  hour party
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator scales this amount slightly with party duration
                and total number of guests (adults + kids).
              </p>

              <h2>Tips for planning drinks for different types of parties</h2>

              <h3>Cocktail party / aperitivo</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Increase the share of <strong>spirits</strong> and
                  <strong>ice</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Offer at least one <strong>signature cocktail</strong> plus a
                  simple long drink (e.g., gin & tonic).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Keep plenty of <strong>sparkling water</strong> and
                  <strong>non‑alcoholic options</strong> for drivers.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Family birthday with kids</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Lower the <strong>alcohol share</strong> and increase
                  <strong>soft drinks, juice and water</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider <strong>non‑alcoholic sparkling drinks</strong> so
                  kids can join the toast.
                </li>
                <li>Use smaller glasses to reduce waste and sugar intake.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Dinner party</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Plan
                  <strong>1 bottle of wine for every 2–3 adults</strong> for a
                  full dinner.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Add some <strong>aperitif</strong> (prosecco, spritz) and
                  <strong>digestifs</strong> if appropriate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always have <strong>still and sparkling water</strong> on the
                  table.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How far in advance should I buy drinks?</h3>
              <p>
                Spirits and wine can be bought well in advance. Beer is best
                stored cool and away from light. Buy ice and fresh ingredients
                (fruit, herbs, juice) on the day of the event if possible.
              </p>

              <h3>What if some guests do not drink alcohol?</h3>
              <p>
                Increase the number of non‑alcoholic drinks and lower the
                alcohol share. As a rule, plan at least
                <strong>2–3 non‑alcoholic drinks per non‑drinker</strong> for a
                3–4 hour party.
              </p>

              <h3>How much extra should I buy?</h3>
              <p>
                It is usually safe to add a <strong>10–20% buffer</strong> on
                top of the calculator’s result, especially for popular items
                like water, beer and your main wine. Unopened bottles can often
                be stored or returned.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I switch to metric or US units?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator internally uses milliliters and liters, but the
                results are shown in bottles, cans and liters, which work well
                in both metric and US contexts. You can think of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>750 ml wine bottle ≈ 25.4 fl oz</li>
                <li>330 ml beer ≈ 11.2 fl oz</li>
                <li>700 ml spirit bottle ≈ 23.7 fl oz</li>
              </ul>
            </section>
